  "prompt": "What are Audio Codecs?",
  "response": "Audio codecs (codec = compression/decompression) are technologies used to encode and decode digital audio files, enabling audio compression and transmission. Here's a detailed overview:\n\n1. Purpose\n- Compress audio files to reduce file size\n- Enable efficient storage and transmission of audio\n- Maintain acceptable sound quality\n\n2. Types of Codecs\na) Lossless Codecs\n- Preserve original audio quality\n- Examples: FLAC, ALAC, WAV\n- Larger file sizes\n\nb) Lossy Codecs\n- Reduce file size by removing less perceptible audio data\n- Examples: MP3, AAC, OGG\n- Smaller file sizes\n- Some quality loss\n\n3. Common Audio Codecs\n- MP3: Most popular, good compression\n- AAC: Higher quality than MP3\n- WAV: Uncompressed, high quality\n- FLAC: Lossless compression\n- OGG: Open-source alternative\n- WMA: Windows Media Audio\n\n4. Characteristics\n- Bit rate\n- Sample rate\n- Compression ratio\n- Audio channels\n- File size\n\n5. Applications\n- Music streaming\n- Digital audio players\n- Broadcasting\n- Video/multimedia production\n\nAudio codecs are crucial for efficient digital audio storage and transmission.",
